<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Head.</emphasis>
Not protruding from the body; face very distinctly oblique (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Fig. 1. Amorphopus notabilis (female). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395606" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">1B, C</figureCitation>
); antennae filiform with 15 segments, inserted below the eyes; vertex anteriorly truncated and equal in width to one of the eyes; frontal costa with a wide scutellum between the lower part of the eyes, slightly compressed-elevated, sinuate below; eyes globose, not prominent; posterior ocelli placed between the inferior part of the eyes (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Fig. 1. Amorphopus notabilis (female). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395606" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">1B</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Thorax.</emphasis>
Meso-pleura expanding to the sides and covering the coxae in dorsal view. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Pronotum.</emphasis>
Macropronotal and strongly depressed dorso-ventrally. Lateral view. Median carina slightly undulated on prozona and extended to pronotal disc apex, prozonal carina and humero-apical carina visible, reaching the sulci; tegminal and ventral sinus present; length of the infrascapular area mid-sized covering to first abdominal tergite; humeral angles obtuse (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Fig. 1. Amorphopus notabilis (female). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395606" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">1A</figureCitation>
). Dorsal view. anterior and posterior margins truncated, also the first one undulated; prozonal carina visible; lateral lobes of pronotum ampliate and projected sideways, with the margins undulated and with a blunt spine (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Fig. 1. Amorphopus notabilis (female). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395606" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">1D</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Wings.</emphasis>
Tegmina and hind wings developed; tegmina ovoid, hind wings as long as the pronotum apex, opaque with the apical veins between the C and Sc yellowish. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Legs.</emphasis>
Fore and middle femora rectangular, longer than wide and with margins undulated (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Fig. 1. Amorphopus notabilis (female). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395606" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">1E, F</figureCitation>
), fore and middle tibiae narrow and short. Hind femur with the pre-genicular tooth slightly developed, small foliose plate present between the ventro and dorso-external carinae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Fig. 1. Amorphopus notabilis (female). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395606" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">1D</figureCitation>
), hind tibia narrow and with few spines on the meso-distal portion. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Narrow and slim, subgenital plate with the distal edge wavy with a rounded prolongation in the middle (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Fig. 1. Amorphopus notabilis (female). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395606" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">1G</figureCitation>
); ovipositor with narrow valves and with denticulations of moderate size (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Fig. 1. Amorphopus notabilis (female). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395606" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">1H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Male.</emphasis>
Similar to the female, except for the post-abdomen characters (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Fig. 2. Amorphopus notabilis (male). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395607" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">2A-F</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate moderately prolonged, with the dorsal edge straight and the apex rounded (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Fig. 2. Amorphopus notabilis (male). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395607" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">2G</figureCitation>
), conical and robust cerci (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Fig. 2. Amorphopus notabilis (male). A. Habitus in lateral view; B. Frons; C. Head, lateral lobes of pronotum and tegmina in lateral view; D. Habitus in dorsal view; E. Fore-femur; F. Mid-femur; G. Terminalia in ventral view; and H. In lateral view." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395607" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">2H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Coloration.</emphasis>
Predominantly white with scattered gray spots. Face and ventral surface of the body black with scattered whitish bands; pronotal disc from the level of the third pair of coxae with gray stripes, which extend and alternate towards the posterior area of the pronotum; fore femur white, fore tibia black with a white ring in the mesal region; femur and mid tibia, as well as the basal half of the hind femur, light pink, distal half of the hind femur white with gray stripes in similar appearance to the pronotal disc (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig. 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Fig. 3. Live Amorphopus notabilis from Brazilian Amazon." figureDoi="10.3897/jor.29.33717.fig3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/395608" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="variation">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Variations</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">The margin undulations of the fore and mid femora may be more conspicuous in some specimens and the lateral lobes with the posterior angles may have sinuato-dentate or serrato-crenate margins.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
